9. A+B represents the logical sum, meaning either A or B or both are true. In the Venn diagram, this includes all areas of both circles (A, B, and their overlap).

10. AÂ·B represents the logical product, meaning both A and B must be true. In the Venn diagram, this would be the area where the two circles overlap.

11. Aâ‡’B means that if A is true, then B must be true. In the Venn diagram, this would show A as a subset of B, where all of A lies within B.

12. While A implies B in the logical sense, it doesn't necessarily mean the alarm caused the burglar, as many other factors could trigger the alarm (ex: malfunction).

13. 
A: The burglar alarm is sounding.
B: The jewelry store window is broken.
C: A masked individual is crawling out of the broken window.
D: The individual is carrying a bag full of expensive jewelry.
E: The masked individual is a burglar.

If A (alarm sounds) and B (window is broken), then something suspicious is happening.
